In [3]:
features = ['bill_length_mm','bill_depth_mm','flipper_length_mm', 'body_mass_g']
km = KMeans(n_clusters=2, random_state=43).fit(p[features])
In [4]:
p['cluster'] = km.predict(p[features])
p.head()

In [10]:
contingency_table = p.groupby(['species','cluster']).size().unstack('cluster', fill_value=0)
contingency_table
Out[10]:
cluster 0 1
species
Adelie 14 132
Chinstrap 5 63
Gentoo 111 8

It looks like the species Adelie and ChinStrap are both put in cluster 1 which means these species must have something incommon. Gentoo is put into cluster 0. It clearly shows there is clear difference between gentoo and the two other species. There is no exact match though. very small percentage of each species is put in the other cluster. This could indicate that a small percentage of a species like gentoo is too different than his own other pengiuns gentoo species. Which makes it put into the other cluster.
